iAfterword:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAs I typed the last character, dawn broke. Since dinner yesterday, I'd		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwritten for 10 hours straight. Searching diaries and materials felt		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilike reliving high school. From early masters like Zhu Kezhen, Su		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBuqing, Ai Qing to today's teachers, people change, but HZ2's teacher		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iculture and atmosphere endure. Becoming a teacher myself, I realized		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHZ2's inclusiveness, unconventionality, and even its teachers'		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifree-spiritedness are unique in Zhejiang, perhaps even rare in Chinese		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ieducation. Sadly, I see their sense of responsibility and integrity is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isomething post-80s/90s teachers may never possess. Here, I salute my		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imentors again—forgive our youthful ignorance! Principal Ye Cuiwei was		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ivoted one of China's Top 10 Most Popular High School Principals in		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i2008—well-deserved. When your classic "E Zhong" became the school		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibroadcast chime, HZ2's greatness, like Peking University's among		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iChinese universities, became unquestionable. When you left home nine		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyears ago, came to this unfamiliar city, and became China's first		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inon-appointed principal through election, the legend of a principal		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand a school began. If possible, I hope to write your biography after		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iretirement—perhaps		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMy Principal, My School		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
